values:
Chip left for Minnesota this morning.&nbsp; 

Twinks arrived at Emerald at around 1am to sleep over.&nbsp; We woke up at 3am, picked up Sison, and headed toward the Chipeco residence at Valle Verde 6.&nbsp; The sadness was apparent during the drive there.&nbsp; Can't believe that may have been the last time I would drive to his house.&nbsp; When we arrived, Efren was already there.&nbsp; Typically Efren, his welcoming remark to us was a simple statement that weighed heavy with insight, &quot;Its fucking March 1, whats up with that??&quot;&nbsp; Just a short while ago, March 1 seemed ages away, and now suddenly it actually is.&nbsp; It's been almost a year since graduation, almost a year since we started the yuppie life, and it marks the month that Chip leaves.&nbsp; MARCH SUCKS ASS.

Inside the Chipeco house, while Chip was getting last minute reminders from Tita Edith, Ef continued his spiel, &quot;Goodbye chair, goodbye wall, goodbye TV, goodbye ref, goodbye cat...&quot;&nbsp; I, on the other hand, was thinking, &quot;Goodbye inumans, goodbye tambayan, goodbye youth&quot;&nbsp; While the boys helped put all the luggages into the car, I heard Tito Jun ask Chip,

&quot;Are you sure you have everything packed...do you have a pen ready for immigration?&quot;
&quot;Yes, pa.&quot;
&quot;Good, then you're ready.&quot;
&quot;No, pa, I'm not.&quot;

Who is ever really READY to go anyway?&nbsp; 

Then, finally, the convoy to the airport.&nbsp; Considering it was 4:30 in the morning, it was a quick drive.&nbsp; Too quick.&nbsp; Before we knew it, we were parked at the Departure area getting our last hugs from Chip.&nbsp; I didn't cry when he hugged me.&nbsp; Hello.&nbsp; I'm not emotional like that. But fuck.&nbsp; When he turned his back, and was slowly walking towards the entrance to the airport, fuck.&nbsp; There were tears.&nbsp; 

Then I started singing &quot;you're leeeaaving on a jetplane, don't know when you'll be back again&quot; then everyone joined in the singing.&nbsp; Jologs na kung jologs. Haha.&nbsp; Efren even put his hands in the air and started waving.&nbsp; We all followed suit.&nbsp; Afterwards, the last glance from Chip.&nbsp; Then, he disappeared.

I've always had difficulty with things like these precisely because I don't know where to begin. Haha. Good thing Sison-not-my-bf is waiting for this, so I'm pressured for time.

1. I hate horror movies, no-brainer movies (not all chick flicks are no-brainers ha!), action movies that are all-action-no-plot, and stressful movies with a lot of deceit.&nbsp; The saying is &quot;Relax, see a movie,&quot; not &quot;scare yourself/lose your brain/tire yourself, see a movie.&quot;

2. I can never go on a serious diet.&nbsp; Good food for me, sadly, are those which doctors call bad. But what the hell, life is short, so why must I deprive myself of what I consider simple joys?

3. I smoke and the only thing that will make me stop is my becoming pregnant...which I don't intend to make happen anytime soon.

4. With regard to friendship, I believe in &quot;a chosen few&quot; over &quot;oh I'm friends with everyone.&quot;&nbsp; If I'm gonna do a despedida, I'll probably have 15 friends over, max.&nbsp; Haha, loser na kung loser.

5. I'm a stickler for time.&nbsp; If I say I'll meet you at 1015, I'll be there at 1015, and if you're late by more than 30 minutes, I'm sure to be pissed off like hell.&nbsp; Of course, this being always on time thing isn't TRUE all the time...but if I have good reason to be late, rest assured I'll let you know before hand.

6.&nbsp; I have a hard time saying No to people.&nbsp; &quot;Sure&quot; is my usual automatic response to friends who wanna go out, family members who send me on errands..etc.&nbsp; And then when something more important comes up, and I back out last minute, people probably can't help thinking I'm just making excuses, but I'm really not.&nbsp; I know its a bad thing...so now, I'm trying my &quot;first-written-on-my-planner, first-serve&quot; rule hehe.&nbsp; But of course, my boyfriend and family are the exceptions to the rule.

7. I'm not the kind of girl who enters a mall and can't help looking at all the stores she passes by.&nbsp; Nah.&nbsp; I can't stand being in a mall for a long period of time just walking around aimlessly.&nbsp; I rarely shop, but when I do, it's a one-time-big-time thing.

8. I'm an impulse buyer for books.&nbsp; I have many books on my shelf that I haven't even opened yet, but still I keep buying more.

9. I love reading fiction from Jude Deveraux, to Rowling, Borges, Murakami, Palahniuk, Salinger, and Shakespeare.&nbsp; Non-fiction lit like biographies, and history bore me.

10. I don't have good hand-eye coordination, or hand-torso-legs coordination for that matter.&nbsp; I'm bad at sports, and I can't dance to save my life.&nbsp; Blame it on being born premature I guess hehe!

11.&nbsp; I love driving sans traffic.&nbsp; 

12. I also love being on busses, trains, and airplanes for the sole reason that I absolutely love the feeling of going somewhere.&nbsp; I have wanderlust.&nbsp; I like to travel and see the world.

13.&nbsp; I'm a beach person.&nbsp; The ocean instills in me a sense of calmness...of serenity.&nbsp; And having a really cold drink while lying down on the sand on a really hot day by the sea is heaven to me.&nbsp; 

14.&nbsp; I am annoyed by people who have bad grammar and/or bad manners (both table etiquette and social graces)

15.&nbsp; This you may find weird: I love being in the spotlight when I do something commendable (awards in school, doing something great at work, etc) but I hate celebrations for my birthday.&nbsp; Hate hate hate.&nbsp; I guess I like the ephemeral attention and approval of people when I achieve something coz it makes me feel that my efforts are appreciated, and but I don't like to get attention just because I got older haha.&nbsp; 

16.&nbsp; The only thing I put on my face is moisturizer.&nbsp; I do not wear make up.&nbsp; Nah-ah.&nbsp; Not even blush or lipstick.&nbsp; 

17.&nbsp; My taste in music is a weird combination: alternative and broadway.&nbsp; Yes, broadway.&nbsp; I memorize almost all the songs in Rent, Jesus Christ Superstar, Phantom of the Opera, and Sound of Music.&nbsp; 

18.&nbsp; I have no problems waking up early, but trust me, the morning-me is just &quot;auto pilot.&quot;&nbsp; No intellectually stimulating activities in the morning please.&nbsp; I'm more productive after lunch, and most productive at night.

19.&nbsp; When I'm sad, I'd rather be alone.&nbsp; I know my friends care for me, and will be there for me as in literally beside me when I'm down, but at my low points, I prefer a solitary moment.&nbsp; 

20. My dream job would be to be a highly paid travel journalist.&nbsp; Asaaa pa.&nbsp; My more realistic job goal would be to start my own events organizing company.&nbsp; That's probably one of my strongest assets now.&nbsp; I am fully confident that I can organize a conference, a party, a wedding, whatever event.&nbsp; 

21.&nbsp; I care about what people think about me.&nbsp; I am open to constructive criticisms about my apperance, my work, my attitude towards things, etc.&nbsp; I will listen to these criticisms, but don't expect drastic shifts from my status quo.&nbsp; 

22. I wanna learn some kind of martial art.&nbsp; I'm incapable of dieting, am not good in sports, find the gym boring...so I'm thinking learning a martial art would be the acceptable exercise for me.&nbsp; God, I need something to balance out all the food, and alcohol I gulp down my throat.

23.&nbsp; I am a generally optimistic person.&nbsp;

24. I see the best in people, and my trust is easily acquired.&nbsp; But once it is broken, it's gonna be very difficult for that person to earn it back again.&nbsp; 

25. I believe in Karma, good and bad.

I've always loved traveling, and I am super thankful that my mom always gets sent on business trips and that she has the money to allow me to tag along.&nbsp; But for quite a while now, I've been feeling this urge inside me to travel on my own, for a longer period of time.&nbsp; And I don't just wanna go on vacation.&nbsp; If I'm gonna go to another country, I'd like to actually go to school, or to go on an internship, AND then go touring on the side.

If I'm gonna get post-grad studies, I'd like to do it in Europe...in the United Kingdom more specifically.&nbsp; Why?&nbsp; Well for a lot of reasons that include the ff:

1. Master's degree programs in the UK only last for ONE YEAR.&nbsp; 

Yessir you read that right.&nbsp; Just one year if you're gonna take them full-time.&nbsp;&nbsp; Just like Sam, and most people brought up here in the Philippines, I have very close family ties and I am very comfortable in what people call my &quot;comfort zone.&quot;&nbsp; But if getting an MS just takes 1 year, pucha, game ako dun!&nbsp; UK pa! Which is, btw, known for business studies.

2. I absolutely LOVE Europe.&nbsp; 

I'm sorry grandma...I'm thankful that you're American, and that made me an American citizen, which is the precise reason I don't need a VISA to most everywhere in the world, but the US really doesn't appeal to me.&nbsp; Hehe!&nbsp; I love Europe and the vast cultural experiences I get whenever I'm there...I love the architecture of the structures, and the history behind them...I love the sense of adventure that continent always instills in me...and I love how it's so different from our country.&nbsp; The Philippines is practically like the US in a downgraded way eh.&nbsp; Food-wise, culture-wise, everything-wise.&nbsp; 

3.&nbsp; It's not so expensive if you think about it in the long-run.&nbsp; 

The Pound sign always scares the hell out of people, and yeah, cost of living is indeed higher in the UK. Pero one year lang naman eh!&nbsp; I've compared this to going to the US, and pucha...as per my cost-benefit analysis, panalo parin UK.&nbsp; For most schools in the states, I'm required to take time-consuming, expensive exams required for admission like the GMAT, the GRE, etc.&nbsp; And, post-grad studies in the States last for at least 2 years.&nbsp; And for my field (business management), some of them even require me to get pre-requisite subjects at their university.&nbsp; Hellloooo hassle.&nbsp; So example, Economics is a pre-req for let's say Quantitative Analysis (subject in masters program)..I have to take Eco (undergrad subject) in that university pa.


Haaaay sana matuloy!&nbsp; I want to get into a scholarship but hello that's a SUPER LONG SHOT coz - I'm not smart enough...and I'm not poor enough either. Haha! Fucker.&nbsp; So malabo ako on both academic merit based, and financial capability based.&nbsp; But nahihiya nako to ask my parents to pay for me eh.&nbsp; haay.&nbsp; Ah basta, September next year, I'm hopefully gonna be outta here.

We are born to die.
- Shakespeare

2008 is the year of suicides.&nbsp; A poet friend of a friend, who appeared to be so full of life, and who wrote the most beautiful poems, suddenly killed herself.&nbsp; Her friends say she tried to make her life into a poem, and when she couldn&rsquo;t reconcile the reality of what is to what it ought to be, she couldn&rsquo;t take it.&nbsp; 

A 24-year old philosophy grad student/teaching assistant locked himself up in a room inside the Ateneo Philosophy Department, sealed all the openings with plastic, and suffocated himself with carbon monoxide by burning charcoal.&nbsp; Evidence suggested it was because of depression, and people who knew him closely say his death was philosophically-natured.&nbsp; 

A college student who starred in the critically acclaimed Tanghalang Ateneo production of Othello killed himself when he found out his girlfriend cheated on him.&nbsp; 

Another college student, who was Ateneo&rsquo;s World Youth Day delegate and a member of the student council, hanged himself when the friend he asked for help in courting a girl, ended up being the girl&rsquo;s boyfriend.&nbsp; His most recent blog entry was also philosophically influenced as it spoke of betrayal and resignation, &ldquo;&hellip;blink, inner peace. in-in-in-inner peace yes this is the answer now, to lull oneself into utopic self-assurances. i have gone from nowhere, to now, here&hellip;the answer now is to dissolve into the great beyond, to get drunk on ideals and the monoliths of virtue&hellip;nakaranas na ako ng WALA, sorry padre&hellip;must finish tonight&hellip;&rdquo;

These are four suicides in the last four months, and it is very disturbing.&nbsp; What&rsquo;s makes it more disturbing aside from the rate is the fact that they are all directly connected to Ateneo, and that the cause of their deaths is indirectly connected to Philosophy.&nbsp; 
May all their souls rest in peace, but I find those four people VERY stupid.&nbsp; 

Philosophy as a required subject, is mainly for mental gymnastics.&nbsp; It aims to exercise your mind, and in doing so, puts you in a state of metaphysical unease, where you find yourself questioning your being, your beliefs, your purpose, etc etc etc.&nbsp; It can serve as an impetus to find yourself, as you grow both in age and wisdom &ndash; that&rsquo;s why it is given in the 3rd and 4th year of college, because at the age range of 19-21, people are supposed to be mature enough for it.&nbsp; It is not a means to an end, and it should not be inappropriately applied to one&rsquo;s problems and confusions.&nbsp; 

 A poet, a grad-student, an actor, a would-be politician.&nbsp; These were four very talented people, who had so much to give to the world, but didn&rsquo;t get the opportunity because of their own doing.&nbsp; What a waste.

In poverty, and in other misfortunes, 
friends are the only refuge.
- Aristotle


&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It took a break-up to seal the friendship.&nbsp; It was 2am on one of the worst nights of my life that my then boyfriend and I broke up.&nbsp; I called Chip to let out the rage, and he told me, &ldquo;Shut up, get some sleep like I was before you called, and I&rsquo;ll meet you at Twinkle&rsquo;s place in the morning.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp; Needless to say, I slept not one wink, and I was already at the lobby of Twinks&rsquo; condo across Ateneo at 7am.&nbsp; The 7-Eleven people refused to sell me beer because of the Quezon City ordinance that forbids them to before 8am.&nbsp; At exactly 8am, I bought three grande bottles of San Miguel for me and made my way to Twinks&rsquo; unit.&nbsp; They were already there.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; And so Chip opened Pandora&rsquo;s box and I started ranting and ranting, not crying, then he hugged me and of course I started crying, because hugging makes people cry.&nbsp; He opened the bottles even if it was absurd to drink beer in the morning, and he drank a little with me even if we had a midterm in Psychology class at 11am.&nbsp; Twinkle acted as the righteous one, and read aloud important stuff from her book, stuff we all had to know before 11am.&nbsp; In retrospect, the scene is pretty funny: one girl crying while drinking beer, one boy consoling while drinking beer, and another girl walking back and forth in between them while reading aloud from a Psychology book, &ldquo;Obsessive-compulsive disorder is a disorder that&hellip;&rdquo;&nbsp; and shouting, &ldquo;Alam niyo, kailangan talaga natin mag aral ngayon...&rdquo;

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That day our friendship was sealed.&nbsp; Chip was officially my college best friend, and I was his, and Twinkle will always be Twinkle pushing her boyfriend and her boyfriend&rsquo;s best friend to do the right thing.&nbsp; Our triumvirate would grow stronger as we went through our college years.&nbsp; We remained intact even when Chip got kicked out of Legal Management, and shifted into Philosophy.&nbsp;&nbsp; Twinkle and I became friends with his new friends, and in fact, my current boyfriend was Chip&rsquo;s blockmate in Philosophy.&nbsp; The three of us would argue for argument&rsquo;s sake because we all thought ourselves to be the best among us three.&nbsp; We&rsquo;d write papers together, and criticize each other&rsquo;s works.&nbsp; We&rsquo;d practice for oral exams together, taking turns at who&rsquo;d play the student and the 2 professors.&nbsp; At the end of the day, we&rsquo;d all have pretty good grades, and we&rsquo;d hang out at Twinkle&rsquo;s condo, watching TV and/or having a drink knowing everything was worth it.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp; Oh, and about that Psychology midterm: I failed it.&nbsp; We got to the classroom on time, and by the time our professor finished giving all the questionnaires to the class, I&rsquo;d have fallen asleep.&nbsp; Chip was seated beside me, and shook me awake.&nbsp; This was useless because I couldn&rsquo;t focus enough to read and comprehend the questions.&nbsp; Good thing, it was a wholly multiple-choice, normal shade-A-B-C-or-D kind of exam, and I just shot gun shaded away.&nbsp; When the results came back, I found out that I got 15/60.&nbsp; I proved the statistical theory that if one is given four choices, he&rsquo;d have a 25% chance of getting the right one, by getting exactly a fourth of the total score even if I was drunk.&nbsp; Haha.&nbsp;

I travel not to go anywhere, but to go.
I travel for travel&rsquo;s sake.&nbsp; The great affair is to move.
- Robert Louis Stevenson

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
&nbsp;For the record, I am not a materialistic person.&nbsp; Regularly shopping for clothes, shoes, and bags do not appeal to me.&nbsp; Aside from a cellular phone, I do not care for gadgets, except for a very primitive model of an ipod to turn off the world when I commute to work everyday.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m not a picky eater, and I abhor spending excessively on food (all eat-all-you-cans are rip-offs.)&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t watch television much, and I&rsquo;d rather buy or borrow DVDs.&nbsp; 

I rarely wear a watch, though I&rsquo;d like to train myself to, so I don&rsquo;t have to get my cell phone when I have to check for the time.&nbsp; I used to love playing tennis, and swimming, but I don&rsquo;t anymore because my chest hurts when I do with my lungs threatening to burst.&nbsp; I smoke, and I can&rsquo;t seem to quit.&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t like sweets, but I love coffee, and I don&rsquo;t get why people like the combination. I don&rsquo;t like being late or canceling appointments if I can help it, because I&rsquo;m sort of a stickler for schedules.&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t like artists that much because I find them weird, but I appreciate works of art.&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t like extremely loud music, and extremely loud persons, for as Desiderata put it, they are vexatious to the spirit.&nbsp; I love reading, but I don&rsquo;t appreciate poetry that much.&nbsp;

 I don&rsquo;t want a big house when I settle down because I like everything to be a few steps away (I&rsquo;m a lazy condominium type); I don&rsquo;t want a big house also because I misplace things easily and I&rsquo;m don&rsquo;t have the willpower to look around a big area; I don&rsquo;t want a big house because I plan to be out of it most of the time&hellip;I may not like many things for many reasons, but if there is one thing I really love and I wish with all my heart that I would have the economic capacity to do, it would be to travel.&nbsp; 

I love cars, busses, trains, and airplanes.&nbsp; I love the feeling of going somewhere &ndash; whether to a local destination, or abroad &ndash; for the sake of going.&nbsp; It doesn&rsquo;t matter if there is a language barrier, or if the place is slightly dangerous, so long as it is new to me.&nbsp; I like the feeling of being mobile, of being in translation.&nbsp; I like going on adventures and experiencing things first hand, for pictures can never satiate this lust.&nbsp; I like the feeling of immersion, of being part of something completely alien to me, even if it&rsquo;s just temporary.&nbsp; I like seeing and learning how different cultures do the most normal things.&nbsp; 

I find it funny how Americans generally have a great penchant for small talk, and how the British always seem polite even when they&rsquo;re angry.&nbsp; I find it slightly irritating that the French enshrine their language so much that they actually refuse to speak English to foreigners even if they know how.&nbsp; I find it weird seeing Mercedes Benzes as taxis in Germany, Peugeots as taxis in France, and Volkswagens as taxis in Mexico, when here in our country, these cars are luxury.&nbsp; Why is marijuana legal in Amsterdam, and why do Japanese love biking so much?&nbsp;

 People ask me why I went to the top of the Empire State, or why I was so excited to go to Anne Frank&rsquo;s house, or why I found it so cool touring the United Nations, or why I bothered to go to the Louvre just to see the Mona Lisa, or why I went to Versailles just to see King Louie&rsquo;s room of mirrors, or why I wasted money to watch Les Miserables in London, or the Phantom in New York, and to all these questions, I answered: Because.&nbsp; I can&rsquo;t pinpoint a word to describe the feeling of actually going to those places, so for the lack of better term, I&rsquo;d describe it as &ldquo;surreal.&rdquo;&nbsp; 

Indeed, visiting these places gives me great joy, but while I like being detached from home for a while, I still love the feeling of going back to it more.&nbsp; Yes, no matter how beautiful other countries may be, I would always still long for the Philippines.&nbsp; With all its flaws as a country (the dirt, the traffic, government&rsquo;s inefficiency), its still the only home for me because it is where the people I love are, and it made me who I am.

Ahh&hellip;the Ateneo&hellip;
I&rsquo;ve spent my happiest days there.
- Jose Rizal


Knowledge is elitist.&nbsp; The chances of getting accepted into a top university is directly proportional to how good one&rsquo;s high school is&hellip;and whether luck plays on his side or not.&nbsp; I am not from the likes of Philippine Science (whose graduates usually go through the predicament of choosing which college scholarship offer to accept), or St. Jude (which produces god-like, math-proficient people) or other high schools of outstanding academic reputation.&nbsp; I am from one of the &ldquo;others,&rdquo; and while I will be always proud to be a product of Colegio San Agustin, I cannot pretend that I wasn&rsquo;t one of those who gambled largely on innate intelligence and luck when I took the college entrance exams.&nbsp; Thankfully, I got accepted into the top 4 universities of our country, and I chose to go to the Ateneo.&nbsp; I could not believe I was one of the 2000 students (out of the aspiring 15,000) who actually passed, and I wanted nothing more than to prove that I am a worthy member of this elite group.&nbsp; Proving my worth turned out to be the greatest wrestling match of my life, where my opponent was no one else but myself. 

Adjusting was more than difficult.&nbsp; As a freshman, I had to withstand my professors and their &ldquo;I assume&hellip;&rdquo; lines.&nbsp; &ldquo;I assume you have learned (insert topic) in high school, so we may now begin with (insert topic of next level) now.&rdquo; &ldquo;I assume you people know how to read and to comprehend and to do so speedily&hellip;I want chapters 1-4 mastered by tomorrow.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;I assume you have near perfect grammar skills&hellip; criteria for the first paper will be 50% grammar, and 50% content&hellip;if I so much as see a run-on sentence, or a dangling preposition, it will be your doom.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp;

 I&rsquo;m not sure if the others felt the same way, but I was extremely intimidated by these statements.&nbsp; I had to learn to work smart, instead of to work hard.&nbsp; Mere diligence only got me running out of time.&nbsp; I had to re-learn how to read, to get the gist and to drill it into my mind.&nbsp; I had to re-learn speaking in front of an audience, using the appropriate words, driving a point effectively, and appearing to be confident even if my heart was beating 1 million times faster than it should.&nbsp; But the toughest thing I had to deal with was facing the fact that my high school friends who have gone to &ldquo;easier&rdquo; schools, always got the accolades, were always on the dean&rsquo;s list, even if their effort was but a miniscule fraction of mine.&nbsp; Academic pride was very important to me in high school, and I had to swallow the whole cup of it because I knew in my heart that I was getting more out of college. 

By my second year, I had developed a work ethic that was effective for me.&nbsp; I couldn&rsquo;t work during the day, and in parts, so I did everything continuously at night, taking short breaks when needed.&nbsp; I couldn&rsquo;t work without coffee and cigarettes; my brain simply won&rsquo;t function without these substances.&nbsp; I couldn&rsquo;t work way ahead of schedule because the quality of my work suffered from unavoidable laxity; pressure had become the fuel to my creativity and wit.&nbsp;&nbsp; Sleep suddenly was overrated, junk food more appreciated, and alcohol a necessity.&nbsp; A 4-hour shut-eye became the norm, and I couldn&rsquo;t comprehend how other people could sleep the whole 8; what a waste of time!&nbsp; McDonalds, Tapa King, and Yellow Cab comprised my diet.&nbsp; I drank with friends to mourn a pathetic grade, and I drank with friends to celebrate an A; I drank with friends when we had nothing to do, when we had problems, when we just wanted each others&rsquo; company, and the most mundane of days ceased to be insignificant.&nbsp; 

I became aware of my strengths, as well as my weaknesses.&nbsp;&nbsp; I found out that Legal Management was not for me, but I refused to shift out because I loved the dignity coming from Ateneo&rsquo;s School of Management brings, and it was unacceptable for me not to graduate on time.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m very thankful for my friends because we supported each other.&nbsp; Working in groups and peer reviews proved to be helpful and I welcomed constructive criticism.&nbsp; I helped friends with their essays as I was helped with Accounting and Finance. 

Junior year, as it always is, was the most difficult obstacle as academic requirements became more inhumane.&nbsp; At the end of our sophomore year, almost 10 of my friends have either been forced to shift out to other courses or kicked out of school completely, and the filtering did not stop in our third year.&nbsp; The pressure was tougher.&nbsp; I had to juggle my law subjects with management ones and the mind shifts from numerical excel worksheets to flowery sentences in legal texts were almost unbearable.&nbsp; Indeed, mathematical computations translated into hands-on business incubator projects, and the memorization of legal provisions translated into sound arguments did not mix.&nbsp; 

In addition to that, this was also the year level when Philosophy and Theology became heavy burdens.&nbsp; No matter what one&rsquo;s course was, he was required to take 12 units of Philosophy and 12 units of Theology along with other core subjects, in addition to their major subjects.&nbsp; And to say that Jesuit education in these areas was intense was an extreme understatement.&nbsp; Imagine racking your brains out trying to come up with an eloquent explanation of Being or of Nothingness or trying to articulate &ldquo;that which makes a thing what it is,&rdquo; parallel to a human person&rsquo;s existence (what comprises the &ldquo;I&rdquo; of your person?).&nbsp; Then when you finally get it, the euphoria is short-lived because you realize this is only 1 of the 10 thesis statements you have to master for oral exam day.&nbsp; And you can&rsquo;t make bola your professor because what is measured is the tightness of the thinking process you&rsquo;ve exuded and not how cool your answer sounds.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s mind-boggling, and you just want to sleep for 100 hours after the exam, but then you can&rsquo;t because you have a Marketing midterm the next day.&nbsp; By the end of the year, around 30 LM students have been kicked out, and though I was one of those hanging by a thread, I thank God I wasn&rsquo;t one of them. 

When senior year came, I told myself I had to make a dent in the system that has molded me for the past three years.&nbsp; I had to make the dean&rsquo;s list come hell or high water.&nbsp; After all, I was not the same person I was in my freshman year; I had adjusted and I was made of sterner stuff this time.&nbsp; The battle was three-fourths done, and I had come to thrive with the pressure, romancing the struggle in a relationship of love and hate.&nbsp; I didn&rsquo;t feign confidence anymore; I had it at my beck and call.&nbsp; Not coming from a very reputable high school was immaterial because every one of us left was now a true Atenean.&nbsp; I no longer shuddered at a 50-page paper, I said, &ldquo;Bring it on!&rdquo;&nbsp; I no longer cringed at another business audit project; I looked forward to it.&nbsp; Give me 100 pages to read tonight, and I said, sure, I&rsquo;ll give you a substantial 3-page summary and oral report tomorrow morning.&nbsp; Give me five long tests in one day, and I still assured you a good grade.&nbsp; My mantra was: Fire on me your biggest guns, Ateneo, and I guarantee I&rsquo;ll retaliate in the way you expect me to, and more, because you have taught me well.&nbsp; 

In the end, I was indeed on the dean&rsquo;s list&hellip;for both the first and second semester.&nbsp; I remember, I wasn&rsquo;t even able to attend the Honors&rsquo; Assembly because I watched a Lea Salonga concert that night.&nbsp; &ldquo;Sayang naman,&rdquo; my boyfriend told me, &ldquo;Ngayon ka lang aakyat ng stage.&rdquo; And I said, &ldquo;Lea matters more&hellip;and besides, what&rsquo;s a certificate?&nbsp; Isn&rsquo;t it nothing but ink on paper?&rdquo;

Why do we study the Greek and Roman Classics?&nbsp; What makes these ancient literary works relevant today, more than 2000 years after they were first written? 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In a nutshell, it is because they have defined humanity.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Without any external influence, or attempt to study the past, humanity is only as old as a person is.&nbsp; So for a young person like myself who is 21 years old, humanity has only existed for a quarter of a century as well.&nbsp; But 21 years is even less than a dot on the whole painting we call humanity, and we can never understand the whole picture without attempting to understand those who have come and gone before us.&nbsp; And that is why we study history, and literature for that matter &ndash; so we can try to grasp the attitudes, values, and ideals that have formed the human race through the years, and in the process, molded the culture our generation has been born into.&nbsp; By studying and reflecting on who came before us, we come to know who we are, and who would be better to study and reflect on than those who have defined humanity itself?&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Greeks (who influenced the Romans) have defined humanity because they are credited for being the pioneers in asserting ideas on what is good, right, and beautiful, and although there are many flaws in their culture (discrimination of women, slavery, homosexuality), the ideas they have begun have become the ideals we all aspire for today precisely because Greek culture is the basis of Western culture and identity as we know it at present.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So what is Greek culture anyway?&nbsp; How similar or different is it from ours?

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The earliest known product of Greek literature is the Iliad by Homer.&nbsp; The story begins in medias res, in the 10th year of the Trojan War.&nbsp; The Greeks live by a certain guest-host-friendship agreement, where the beneficiary of gifts gain honor, while the benefactor gains alliance for future needs. And we know that the war came about because Paris, prince of Troy, broke this agreement with the Achaeans when he eloped with Helen, Queen of Sparta.&nbsp; In an appropriate angry response to this, Menelaus, Helen&rsquo;s husband, sought the help of his brother, Agamemnon, in waging war with the Trojans, for 2 reasons: a.) to get Helen back, and more importantly, b.) to save face.&nbsp;

 It must be noted that the Greeks are characterized by a Shame culture, where the greatest risk is dishonor, or what they call the loss of time (respect from peers in one&rsquo;s lifetime).&nbsp; The only way to redeem oneself, in a Greek point of view, is through revenge, and the achievement of kleos (glory; immortalized in art after one&rsquo;s death) in a moment of aristeia (moment of glory; moment one achieves kleos).&nbsp; Achilles, the Achaeans&rsquo; best warrior in the war, is the perfect embodiment of this process.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Today, the guest-host-friendship agreement is still very much manifested in our life, especially in foreign relations.&nbsp; One example would be when our president, Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo, because the US has always given us economic aid, expressed her all-out support for the USA&rsquo;s &ldquo;war on terror,&rdquo; even if she knew (well I&rsquo;d like to think that she did) that that whole Iraq thing is so utterly stupid.&nbsp; In 2005, she came to her senses when a Filipino was held hostage in Iraq and GMA backed out from the Coalition of the Willing.&nbsp; 

It&rsquo;s funny that she was the first one to join the coalition and she was also the first to leave.&nbsp; In contrast to the Greeks, however, our culture is not a Shame culture, but a Guilt culture.&nbsp; Being &ldquo;the best&rdquo; in our respective fields (ar&ecirc;te) never outweighs the outlook of conscience and morality we have in everything we do.&nbsp; I think this is because we are Christians, who believe that that the good would be generously rewarded by God in the after-life, unlike the Greeks, who believe that man becomes a mere &ldquo;shade of himself&rdquo; &ndash; insignificant, and unworthy &ndash; after death.&nbsp; As the shade of Achilles states in Book 11 of Homer&rsquo;s next epic, the Odyssey, &ldquo;I&rsquo;d rather live working as a wage laborer with no land&hellip;than lord over the wasted dead.&rdquo;

In comparison to Homer&rsquo;s ar&ecirc;te, Roman writer Virgil speaks about pietas, which means dutifulness in the highest degree, or the steadfast commitment to one&rsquo;s destiny/calling.&nbsp; While the Iliad is about individual time, revenge, and kleos, and the Odyssey is about nostos or homecoming, the Aeneid is about so much more, about something much deeper.&nbsp; More than individual glory or a safe homecoming, the Aeneid is about fulfilling Aeneas&rsquo; destiny of founding Rome.&nbsp; By inserting a sense of divine mission in his literary work, Virgil has deepened the Homeric values in a way that is unique to him; according to him, &ldquo;It is the lack of pietas that causes misfortune.&rdquo;&nbsp; Aeneas, the protagonist of the story, is an exemplary embodiment of pietas because of his steadfast commitment to his destiny despite feeling hopeless, helpless, and finding love along the way.&nbsp; His love interest in the story is Dido, who because of being overcome by passion and emotion, forgot her husband too quickly, forgot her role as queen, and in the end, died, when Aeneas left her.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Today, it is a very rare and wonderful thing to know what one&rsquo;s calling is; and it is even more wonderful if you actually get to pursue it.&nbsp; With the myriad options available, the influence of the media, and the fast-paced lifestyle everyone lives by, it has become a difficult task to find time for solitary reflection and to discover one&rsquo;s true identity.&nbsp; And it doesn&rsquo;t help that unlike Homer and Virgil&rsquo;s stories, we now don&rsquo;t have gods who actively help us when we need it, and who tell us what our calling or destiny is.&nbsp; In contrast to the characters in those stories who know what they are born to do, the paradigm instilled to us now by our elders is that, &ldquo;You make your own destiny.&rdquo;&nbsp; So, in a sense, our life is arguably more difficult because it is up to us to discover our own calling AND up to us to be fully committed to its pursuit.&nbsp; But regardless of the modern impediments to find our mission in life, the important thing is that once we discover what it is, we must pursue it wholeheartedly with pietas, and not let anything stop us from becoming the person we were born to be. 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Another famous Greek literary work is Agamemnon by Aeschylus.&nbsp; This is the tragic story of the House of Atreus.&nbsp; The theme of the tragedy is philos-aphilos, or hate-in-love.&nbsp; Agamemnon is succession of complex collisions, with each character acting with an immense force of passion.&nbsp; Agamemnon is a man full of pride, and the passion for power.&nbsp; Because of these attributes, he conquered most of Greece, sacrificed his daughter Iphigeneia, sacked Troy, and brought back home a beautiful mistress named Cassandra.&nbsp; Clytaemnestra, his wife, responded to these actions with a passionate force as well.&nbsp; Her love for her daughter Iphigeneia resulted in hatred for Agamemnon leading her to take his cousin Aegisthus as a lover, and killing Agamemnon upon his homecoming.&nbsp; Ironically, she still had love for Agamemnon in spite of everything for she also killed Cassandra in a jealous rage.&nbsp; Indeed, Agamemnon is a tale of passion and revenge, with each tragic event having a consequence in another tragic event, until finally, Orestes (Agamemnon&rsquo;s son) comes home and kills both Clytaemnestra and Aegisthus, thereby bringing justice to all the heinous crimes committed by the couple, and putting everything back into balance.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Parallel to this are two other notable tragedies, which are: Oedipus Rex and Antigone by Sophocles.&nbsp; Oedipus, like Agamemnon, is also a person with great pride or hubris &ndash; which was of course his tragic flaw or hamartia &ndash; and when pride for wealth and power become too great for even wisdom to restrain, one&rsquo;s downfall is assured.&nbsp; This is exactly what happened to Oedipus; he brought his fate upon himself because of who he was.&nbsp; Because he was self-sufficient, he ran away from Corinth, thinking he could escape the prophecy of him killing his father and marrying his mother by leaving who he thought were his natural parents; this of course brought him to Thebes, where he unknowingly met his real father, and thereafter fulfilled both prophecies.&nbsp; Because he was daring, he killed Laius, who was he real father.&nbsp; Because he was intelligent, he solved the riddle, which gave him the right (by popular demand) to marry the queen of Thebes, Jocasta, who was in reality his real mother.&nbsp; And finally, because he had a sense of public spirit, he ironically, investigated the murder of Laius, leading him to find out it was he who was the murderer after all.&nbsp; After that, he blinded himself literally when he was no longer blind figuratively.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After both Oedipus and Jocasta died, their sons Eteocles and Polyneices fought over the kingship of Thebes, but in the end both died at each other&rsquo;s hands.&nbsp; Creon, their maternal uncle, got the crown.&nbsp; Creon refused to have Polyneices&rsquo; body buried, but Antigone, his sister, buried him anyway.&nbsp; Antigone was simply obeying the divine law, which speaks of the solemn duty of women to perform the funeral rites of their dead.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All the victims in the tragedies bring their pre-destined fate upon themselves precisely because of their character, because of who they are.&nbsp; Pride is a tragic flaw that assures its possessor his downfall.&nbsp; But today, pride isn&rsquo;t a flaw that&rsquo;s common among people; rather, it is greed.&nbsp; People of the present, especially the youth, always want more than what they need.&nbsp; We are a materialistic generation, with three words constantly ringing in our minds: consume, consume, consume.&nbsp; We want more clothes, more bags, more cars, more jewelry.&nbsp; We gamble, and if we win, we gamble more to win more.&nbsp; And this is our downfall for the more we want more, the more we lose in the end, because we can&rsquo;t win all the time.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; One example of a Greek comedy is Lysistrata by Aristophanes.&nbsp; This is a tale of women, led by Lysistrata, who withhold sex from their husbands until they sign a treaty of peace to end the Peloponnesian War.&nbsp; This play depicts the attempt of women to contribute their thoughts about society and policy-making in a patriarchal society.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The play&rsquo;s anti-war theme is very much relevant today given the Iraq situation.&nbsp; In the Peloponnesian War, the conflict was between Athen and Sparta &ndash; two nations that shouldn&rsquo;t be fighting, but helping each other because they are of the same heritage.&nbsp; Now, the conflict is primarily between the Americans and the people of Iraq.&nbsp; These people shouldn&rsquo;t be fighting each other as well because although they don&rsquo;t have the same heritage, both these races &ndash; along with all humans &ndash; belong to one race, which is the human race.&nbsp; We should help each other out in times of need and exist amicably side-by-side instead of killing each other.&nbsp; Indeed, war is a very ugly thing and nothing good could possibly come out of it.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Undeniably, our culture is so much different from that of the Greeks.&nbsp; But even if this is so, theirs is a culture that is worth reflecting upon deeply.&nbsp; The ideals of arete, and pietas, are values we must strive for today in everything we do; we must always aim to be the best in our respective fields, settling with nothing less than excellence, and we must always have a steadfast commitment to our calling, or to anything we begin to endeavor.&nbsp; Furthermore, we must always be wary of hubris, remembering that pride is a tragic flaw that assures our downfall, as well as all the other human flaws we are so prone to like greed, sloth, or lust.&nbsp; Finally, we must reflect deeply on the fact that war was despised even 2000 years ago, as it should be now.&nbsp; War is a useless, stupid, thing brought about by hate and greed, and the world would be a much, much better place if this did not exist at all.

&nbsp;&nbsp; Back in high school, I liked the idea of learning and getting high grades and I got them.&nbsp; Being the top of the class was a tradition and this proved to be worth it because come college, I got accepted into the Ateneo de Manila University.&nbsp; This looked like an opportunity to uphold my tradition of academic excellence because after all, Ateneo has its own tradition of producing excellent students.&nbsp; However, as the merely average QPIs kept on arriving, this became a reality check and some changes in my viewpoint on life began.&nbsp; Thus, I would say that my being an Atenean is a constant struggle between the tradition of excellence I wish I still had and the innovation of my character because I don&rsquo;t have it.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp; One reality check I&rsquo;ve gotten here in school happened very recently when a reflection paper was returned and for the first time ever, I got a low grade for an essay. In my opinion, people try to get things perfect in art because it&rsquo;s really hard to do so in real life; they impart some valuable message through a perfect movie or poem, and, trigger some hidden emotion through a perfect painting or song.&nbsp; For me, I&rsquo;ve always tried to perfect the art of writing an essay, putting in flare without compromising the content or my honesty, so when my paper came short of perfection, it proved to be quite a shattering experience and a big break in my daily life because I thought I more or less had mastery over that art.&nbsp; But I wasn&rsquo;t really depressed or anything because as the saying goes: charge it to experience.&nbsp; Besides, unlike before, I&rsquo;ve already realized that letter grades aren&rsquo;t the measure of who I am, though they do prove to be effective roots for reflection.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Excellence for me now is not limited by getting an A, though As do create a big smile on my face, but by accepting constructive criticism and giving it another shot.&nbsp; That experience pushed me farther away from the tradition I once had and nearer to the innovation of me.&nbsp; But by attempting to innovate myself, I am once again pushed back in the direction of excellence and I again find myself in the middle, where the tension is felt the most.
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp; Another illustration of this tug-of-war is my complacency.&nbsp; Being accepted into one of the country&rsquo;s most prestigious universities had effected on me some &ldquo;side effects&rdquo; so to speak.&nbsp; I became complacent because I had the impression that once one becomes an Atenean, a good future is guaranteed.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This is one personal &ldquo;truth&rdquo; which I&rsquo;m pretty sure attained universal status, because I think most Ateneans used to or worse, still think this way.&nbsp; However, studying in the Ateneo does not ensure one of a stable future.&nbsp; In fact, it doesn&rsquo;t give a person anything except the bragging right of being able to call oneself an &ldquo;Atenean.&rdquo;&nbsp; But then being labeled an Atenean does not automatically define a person, despite the stereotype (that Ateneans are eloquent, intelligent, etc.), because it is through one&rsquo;s individual character that he will be judged.&nbsp; Studying in the Ateneo is a privilege and each student must maximize this and hone his skills in order to truly embody the stereotype of what an Atenean ought to and is expected to be.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp; It would be very fulfilling for me, for example, if people would recognize that I am an Atenean not because I&rsquo;m wearing an Ateneo jacket or ID strap but because of the way I act or speak or write.&nbsp; If through my demeanor, I am recognized to be an Atenean, then the label of being one is not anymore constrained to the logo on the jacket, but rather, the label would be as if it were innately embedded on my forehead, visible wherever I go &ndash; and that would be a true mark of excellence.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At this point, it is noticeable that the concept of excellence has evolved from one of a purely academic nature into one that is deeper and more mature.&nbsp; This evolution, ironically, springs from the innovation of my character.&nbsp; I say it is ironic because in the first part, tradition and innovation were opposite poles creating a tension, but now, it has started to evolve into something else.&nbsp; As I am constantly being pushed and pulled in this tug-of-war, making me a seemingly passive object, I gradually transform into an active participant because I also attempt to pull these two poles together, and this essentially sums up what I am as an Atenean.&nbsp; Ultimately, my being an Atenean is my personal struggle to transform the tension between the tradition of excellence and the innovation of character into a wonderful juxtaposition that brings out the best of both sides...and hopefully, the best of who I am.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; And it would be very cool if I could do that.

*published for Katipunan magazine&nbsp;  
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Freshmen Orientation Seminar (ORSEM) can either be a very memorable or a very forgettable 3-day event.&nbsp; Held every year during the week before classes officially begin, freshmen either see it as an unnecessary requirement of going to school early, or a productive introduction for what&rsquo;s in store for them in the next four years. It has gone a long, long way since its inception when there was more grass than buildings in the college area, and the number of people in the covered courts was less than half of number now.&nbsp; And this year, aside from the whopping increase in the student population, the ORSEM itself has undergone drastic changes that brought shockwaves to the ORSEM committee, its volunteers, and even the alumni.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Three major events highlight the 3 ORSEM days: the departmental talks, the campus tours, and the organization tours (orgtours).&nbsp; These have always been the core agenda for the freshmen up until four years ago when the School of Management (SOM) first held the SOM Night, which became an additional major event for the SOM students. Betsy Grozman, a present psychology professor and an Ateneo alumna, stated that in the early 90s (she didn&rsquo;t say what year exactly so as not to divulge her age), the freshmen batch comprised of approximately only 800 students, orgs could be easily counted and memorized and buildings such as SEC, CTC, and SOM were &ldquo;nothing but grass, grass, grass.&rdquo; Jose Ma. Edito Tirol, a present history professor and an Ateneo alumnus as well (freshmen batch 1990), stated the same except that he didn&rsquo;t remember anything about the orgtours because he thought of it as a &ldquo;waste of time.&rdquo;&nbsp; Nevertheless, with relatively fewer people, fewer orgs, and fewer buildings, finding out that they never ran during the campus and org tours was not surprising at all.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, as the years passed by, student population grew immensely from formerly having only the School of Arts and Sciences and one dean for everyone, to presently having four different schools, and four different deans.&nbsp; Also, a lot of student organizations were accredited in the last 15 years, and new buildings were also erected.&nbsp; Consequently, the ORSEM evolved into a much busier event with numerous stops for the campus and org tours, and with lots of upperclassmen volunteers making sure each block gets to each stop, spends equal time at it, and gets the necessary information.&nbsp; 

Hence, the running &ndash; which everyone seems to make a big fuss about.

Has the ideally fun, efficient, productive ORSEM indeed become a tiring, ineffective, waste of time?

Apparently, lots of parents and students think so.&nbsp; The administration has, in the last few years, received complaints of how tiring and ineffective the ORSEM was.&nbsp; And in parallel to that, the administration thinks that the ORSEM does not effectively give the freshmen an insight of the values held so dear primarily because the freshmen become so exhausted from running and they don&rsquo;t remember the details well because of the information overload they get.

In this context, the admin acts this year by effecting big, big changes.

In an interview with Mrs. Assunta Cuyegkeng, VP for the Loyola Schools, who speaks in behalf of the administration, she explained the major changes they proposed to the ORSEM committee, and the rationale behind them:

1. To decongest the ORSEM &ndash; The freshmen don&rsquo;t need to know everything about Ateneo in 3 days.&nbsp; For example, how effective is it to talk about Ignatian spirituality to 2100 freshmen for a few minutes? This is a very important topic that merits a more focused approach, one that creates a deeper impact.&nbsp; Another example is the effectivity of visiting 40-plus org booths in 2 hours, with some of the orgs promoting the stuff of their sponsors on the side. The admin puts value on the non-academic formation of our students through the orgs, but would it not be better to have more focus through cluster presentations in the various AVRs?

2. To shorten the hours &ndash; The admin thinks that the registration need not start at 6:30am because it will mean that some people have to leave their houses very early and stay till late in the afternoon. Admin suggested that some of the sessions be incorporated on other occasions such as InTACT, Org Recruitment week, etc.

3. To think about how their actions will reflect on the values of Ateneo - Perhaps, to teach them on their first days, that they are responsible for doing certain things by themselves and not depend on others: segregating their was waste, throwing garbage in the right places, etc. Or perhaps&mdash;because we seek the truth-- to tell true stories instead of urban legends.
Other minor changes were also proposed.&nbsp; The JGSOM freshmen were always asked to wear green on their first day for the past several years, and in the context of the Ateneo-La Salle rivalry, the dean of the SOM asked the ORSEM committee to choose another color.&nbsp; It must be noted, though, that SOSE students wore green.&nbsp; Another change proposed is that the bullhorn sirens be removed and instead be replaced with the synchronization of the chimes.&nbsp; The admin thinks that the sirens sound like alarm sirens so it would be difficult to distinguish when a real emergency occurs.&nbsp; However, this proposed change did not take effect and the sirens were still used like before.&nbsp; 

And so the ORSEM pushed through with Day 1 and Day 2 having the core agenda (dept talks and campus tours) those days were originally planned with.&nbsp; But come June 15, the biggest impact of the administration&rsquo;s suggestions for changes took place, and its impact was greatly felt.

Instead of the usual org tours held at the SEC building, the freshmen were instead put in the 8 different venues namely Escaler, Sec Lec B, Sec Lec C, CTC 105, the Ching Tan Room, Faura AVR, the Soc Sci AVR, and the Bell AVR.&nbsp; Instead of the freshmen going from room to room to view the different presentations of every organization, the organizations were grouped into clusters and were made to present in every venue.&nbsp; 

This was definitely a drastic change.&nbsp; 

But was the change a counter-culture approach to an event that was long since established and already considered tradition?&nbsp; Or was it a necessary enhancement of a culture that is great but could be greater?

A freshman from AB Interdisciplinary Studies commented that, &ldquo;it was a relief not to run around like they did the day before (campus tours).&rdquo;&nbsp; But then another freshman from BS Legal Management stated that &ldquo;it was better to run around than stay in the covered courts and then suddenly go to an aircon but &lsquo;boring&rsquo; venue&rsquo; because at least he wouldn&rsquo;t get sick and wouldn&rsquo;t fall asleep.&rdquo;

And so it all boils down to a matter of perspective.

This year is the first time that the org tours were replaced with &ldquo;orgtalks&rdquo; and the effectivity of which cannot be easily judged.
Yes, the freshmen didn&rsquo;t have to run.&nbsp; Yes, they weren&rsquo;t tired.&nbsp; Yes, they weren&rsquo;t forced to digest an overload of information in such a short time.&nbsp; But the trade-offs of these cannot be easily disregarded too.&nbsp; For one, with 2100 freshmen this year being fit into the 8 AVRs made it inevitable that they become like sardines forced to fit in a can.&nbsp; There simply isn&rsquo;t enough room.&nbsp;
 Monoblock chairs were put on the aisles, front, and back parts of the AVRs to accommodate all the freshmen, the ORSEM volunteers sat on the floor, and the other clusters waiting for their turn to present had to wait outside.&nbsp; Also, the orgs are forced to unite with their fellow orgs in their respective cluster, thereby making creativity of presentation limited because of the limited time per cluster.&nbsp; And furthermore, a lot of freshmen on Day 3 this year seem to view the org presentations as a comfortable venue for them to rest and fall asleep.

And so, the counter-culture and culture enhancement view on the change depends on who reacts to it.&nbsp; And the judgment of the pros and cons of it lies on the compromise of the admin and the ORSEM committee.

Given the whopping increase in student population every year, would the ORSEM next year stick with the new orgtalks now or would they go back to the traditional orgtours?&nbsp; 

The evaluation of the change is yet to be done, and the effect of which is yet to be seen.&nbsp; We all just have to wait and see for next year&hellip;.

&nbsp;&nbsp; I think I was 14 years old when I first heard the word holocaust.&nbsp; My mom and I were in Amsterdam and of course, we visited the house of Anne Frank.&nbsp; I even remember cursing every 5 minutes or so because all the staircases (there were a lot) were abnormally steep.&nbsp; We even had to walk through this little hidden door to get into the attic where she hid for more than 2 years.&nbsp; Hassle.&nbsp; And being a young and stupid girl, all I thought of was, &ldquo;Who the hell was the architect of this house?&nbsp; He should be burning in hell now.&rdquo;&nbsp; Anyway because of that, you could imagine how much of the tour guide&rsquo;s lecture got stuck in my brain: close to none.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As I grew older however, I got to learn a little more info regarding the matter (Sir, you are welcome to correct any errors because this is all stock knowledge).&nbsp; I got to know the city most devastated in the Second World War: Warsaw, Poland.&nbsp; I know the country that suffered the greatest loss of life: the USSR.&nbsp; I know the number of deaths: A LOT (a little over 30 million?).&nbsp; I know, even if vaguely, the details of the war: the dates, the people involved, the start and end etc.&nbsp; I know the horrible facts and figures, and these trigger various emotions, opinions, and judgments from different people, but ultimately I guess it just baffles us.&nbsp; We try our best to comprehend the war, the atrocity, the cause, and we use statistics to help us understand the history.&nbsp; But then now, almost 60 years after it all happened, even the statistics seem illogical.&nbsp; Take 6 million for example &ndash; that single statistic of the murdered European Jews is certainly the most irrational, simply the hardest to grasp.

&nbsp;&nbsp; Hitler wanted to create a &ldquo;perfect&rdquo; race.&nbsp; Consequently, everything and everyone he deemed flawed, he killed.&nbsp; Jews were the scum of the earth in his eyes, hence, his fervent desire to &ldquo;cleanse&rdquo; Europe of this impurity.&nbsp; And so being Fuhrer, he called on the annihilation of the Jews.&nbsp; No other people was chosen for total extermination.&nbsp; No other people was victim of such irrationality.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s what makes the 6M so special.&nbsp; The other 24 million deaths, in contrast, were mere casualties.&nbsp; Casualty by definition is somebody whose death was an indirect result of grave circumstances, in this case, war.&nbsp; The deaths of the Jews were certainly not.&nbsp; On the contrary, their deaths couldn&rsquo;t have been more direct.&nbsp; For Hitler, it was only when all the Jews&rsquo; lives have ended that the war itself will end.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s why he kept on killing Jews despite Germany&rsquo;s defeat being evident.&nbsp; We all know it was a double-edged war with one side portraying political intentions, ergo the need to prove military supremacy, while the other side being rooted in racial concerns, ergo the need to maintain the Aryans&rsquo; firm hold of the apex in the racial hierarchy --- those are the boring facts I have accumulated.&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t even know if what I know is indeed accurate but I don&rsquo;t really care because given that we know all the objective facts and figures of the war and the Anti-Semitic extermination, does this equate full comprehension of the tragedy?&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp; No, because we know the whole thing runs a lot deeper. 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Now we see that statistics isn&rsquo;t enough to understand history.&nbsp; It is only when we give it a human face that we see things more clearly.&nbsp; And in this case, the face is purely Jewish.&nbsp; World War II was about many things, but it was mainly about one very stupid thing &ndash; Hitler&rsquo;s Operation Kill All Jews.&nbsp; 
&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp; One great thing the Jews did was to write things down.&nbsp; Now we have the privilege of reading things like the Diary of Anne Frank (stupid staircases), the diary of Wladyslaw Szpilman, which I am currently reading now (popularly known as the book and movie entitled The Pianist), and of course The Last Days documentary.&nbsp; In the continuum of time, the present is retained in a small measure called moments, which is akin to taking a photograph &ndash; one click and its gone &ndash; forever out of our grasp into the abyss called memory.&nbsp; The memoirs the Jews wrote down serve as a tangible documentation of the tragic moments they had to endure.&nbsp; Now their memories are not only exclusive to themselves and their families, but to the whole world.&nbsp; They did a very humanitarian act if you ask me.&nbsp; Now, long after their death, we have a glimpse of what really transpired in the holocaust 60 years ago.&nbsp; We now can learn and try to interpret the past.&nbsp; And though the whole objective truth can never be reached because of conscious or unconscious bias in the evidence or because of human shortcomings maybe in recording and observing, this is the closest we can get to it.&nbsp; And it&rsquo;s good enough if you ask me.
&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp; In The Last Days, through the memoirs, we see a lot of things obtaining clarity.&nbsp; One is the evident tyranny of tradition on the Germans&rsquo; part.&nbsp; In the footages we see them being controlled by old fears and moreover, hatred to the Jews.&nbsp; We see the spiral effect of the hatred manifested as they gradually deprived the Jews of their rights, property, and livelihood.&nbsp; We also see the next step as the Jews were segregated and ostracized in society by making them live in ghettos, deprived even from the protection of the law.&nbsp; And then we also see in the documentary the situation as the Jews were finally put in those horrible concentration camps.&nbsp; Because of this hatred, unconscious habits and actions had arisen.&nbsp; The Germans, totally brainwashed by Hitler maybe, thought that they were doing the right thing, that the cruelty on the Jews was justified by the cleansing-the-world paradigm.&nbsp; God, were they self-centered pricks all caught up in a belief so wrong, an ideology so fatal.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp; That&rsquo;s the second point: the wrongness of an ideology.&nbsp; We see the stupidity of the idea of a &ldquo;perfect&rdquo; race because we know that there is no such thing.&nbsp; But that&rsquo;s beside the point.&nbsp; If Hitler thought the Aryans were the only pure race, then there is nothing wrong with that; he is entitled to his own opinion.&nbsp; The problem is that because of the belief, he sought the need to completely put the Jews into extinction.&nbsp; No one has the right to do that.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We see in the documentary the 5 lucky survivors retelling and reliving the traumatic memories they have.&nbsp; We see the effects of the stupid ideology and how their supposed impurity was concretized.&nbsp; We see them branded with the yellow star always on their chest, discriminated by their non-Jew neighbors who used to be their closest friends.&nbsp; In short, we see the Jews robbed of&hellip;Life.&nbsp; And they couldn&rsquo;t do anything about it at all.&nbsp; Hitler was god and he sentenced the Jews to a punishment graver than hell &ndash; all because he was so caught up in his hatred and was engrossed with his false ideology.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp; Seeing the tyranny of tradition and the wrongness of an ideology concretized in the memories the survivors shared make us realize just how human &ldquo;great&rdquo; people like Hitler are.&nbsp; We see the capacity of man for good &amp; evil.&nbsp; And so we see the symbiosis of history &amp; humanity.&nbsp; We recognize history not only as an academic discipline, but an aspect in life that all people have a role in.&nbsp; We see in the film how the world was 60 years ago, and all the good and bad things that came with it.&nbsp; We then study this specific part of the past, analyzing the details, interpreting them, in the hope that we could truly understand.&nbsp; What&rsquo;s the point?&nbsp; Well, as you said, sir, &ldquo;To ignore the errors of the past is to condone it.&rdquo;&nbsp; But then it isn&rsquo;t enough, is it?&nbsp; We know that it&rsquo;s not so much the details or statistics that matter, but the values that are imparted through the course of time, and the effect the great tragedy has on human kind.&nbsp; A lot of people died, do we find someone to blame or do we ponder what should be done now and how the past could be used to create a brighter future?&nbsp; That is the essence of the 5 survivors&rsquo; memories, and memory per se for that matter.&nbsp; It is the key to the past &ndash; good or bad &ndash; which gives the unlimited potential of the future.&nbsp; In other words, though memory ignites despair or anguish as in the case of the holocaust, more importantly, it ignites hope.&nbsp; And the symbiosis of memory and hope serves as a guiding light in our venture to the future unknown. 
&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp; To illustrate further: one of the 5 Hungarian Jews in The Last Days was Renee.&nbsp; She was the one who wore her bathing suit under her clothes on her first day at Auschwitz.&nbsp; The bathing suit brought back the good days before the German occupation.&nbsp; It brought back the laughter, the security, the love she once felt.&nbsp; Although the feeling stayed with her for only a short while, it served its purpose: it was her sole source of hope.&nbsp; Renee never lost hope that maybe someday the sun will shine again and life will be good again.&nbsp; And it did, the sun did shine again, maybe not as brightly as before &ndash; because it will never be &ndash; but at least there is light in her life again.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Next in line, we have Irene.&nbsp; She&rsquo;s the one who swallowed the diamonds her mom gave her.&nbsp; Now this is one tough girl.&nbsp; She vowed never to become ash like the thousands around her.&nbsp; Her mommy gave her diamonds to buy bread and that was what she intended to do.&nbsp; She did everything just so that no German will lay a hand on her precious stones.&nbsp; She strived to stay alive for the diamonds and she succeeded.&nbsp; Now, the stones are an heirloom passed down from generation to generation as a symbol of heredity, a memory of the reason for life.&nbsp; Now the grandkids can say, &ldquo;It is because of these diamonds that we are in this world today.&rdquo;

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The other tale that touched me the most was Rob&rsquo;s.&nbsp; He is the guy that when en route to America talked to an American soldier who said, &ldquo;Man, have all the damn bananas and oranges you can eat.&rdquo;&nbsp; That I found really funny and enlightening at the same time.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s a manifestation of life renewed, life suddenly surging through his veins after such a long time of its absence.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Isn&rsquo;t it funny that when things are really bad, we humans can find a driving force to live in such a simple thing like a bathing suit?&nbsp; That life can continue because of a couple of diamonds?&nbsp; That oranges and bananas can be luxurious, even divine?

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Only by giving history a human face do we best understand these things and life itself for that matter.&nbsp; Now, we comprehend that every human being is infinitely valuable with infinite potential.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m sure Renee, Irene, and Rob have kids and grandkids who now are bursting with life, living up their dreams.&nbsp; Those lucky descendants are the products of memory and hope: memory being the foundation, hope the catalyst, and they are the outcome.&nbsp; The memory of death served as the key to life, with hope speeding up the process.&nbsp; But imagine if Renee, Irene, and Rob died.&nbsp; What a total waste of potential.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Now, 60 years after it all happened, the holocaust may still seem hard to grasp.&nbsp; But at least it isn&rsquo;t a complete mystery anymore.&nbsp; Our attempt to understand the past, sans futile ill emotions and blame, gives us the key to brighter future.&nbsp; Now we can be on guard against things like the tyranny of tradition and wrong ideologies because we are already aware of how stories with these components will most likely end.&nbsp; Personally, we can now realize how stupid the whole issue of race is because after all, we all belong to one race, and that is the human race. We realize further the need to accept and not just tolerate the people we deem different from us; when will we learn to see through the eyes of others?&nbsp; It has been said that those who do not learn from history are doomed to repeat it; I say those who do not learn from history are simply doomed.&nbsp;

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If you drive along C5 or Edsa or any main road for that matter, you would most probably notice two kinds of relatively new sedans that are, for lack of better term, abundant.&nbsp; They are the Honda City (the car with chinito lights), and the Chevrolet Optra.&nbsp; And when you do see an Optra and it happens to be white, chances are it&rsquo;s me you see, because there are only a few people in this world who, like me, are compelled by parental parameters to get the cheapest car, ergo base model, ergo only available in white and gold in Chevy&rsquo;s case.&nbsp; Naturally I chose white coz I&rsquo;d rather look like a taxi than a coffin on wheels.&nbsp; Anyway, if you look closer at the white Chevy you see and you notice that it doesn&rsquo;t have an emblem at the back, well congratulations, you&rsquo;ve just encountered my car&hellip;and in a sense, you&rsquo;ve encountered me as well.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; First class is at 930.&nbsp; At 910, I&rsquo;m still at home, inside my car, revving up the engine, listening to it howl.&nbsp; For about 5 minutes I&rsquo;m just sitting there so engrossed in introspection; I&rsquo;m thinking, &ldquo;Do I have my I.D. with me?&nbsp; My cell phone?&nbsp; Smokes?&nbsp; A pen?&nbsp; Oh screw the pen, I&rsquo;ll just borrow one from Anna.&nbsp; Do I have my law book?&nbsp; My Accounting homework?&nbsp; I know I did the damn thing last night, but is it in my bag now?&rdquo;&nbsp; And the litany goes on.&nbsp; You see, I&rsquo;m not exactly an organized person so as the car needs a few minutes to warm up, I too need a few minutes to think.&nbsp; For a while I thought I had OCD because I&rsquo;m always paranoid thinking I forgot something and consequently overly check.&nbsp; But then again I guess my being disorganized and having poor memory is enough justification, huh?

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At 915 I&rsquo;m finally on the road.&nbsp; Shift into first gear and then second and then third, before I know it I&rsquo;m on fifth going on a steady speed of about 90 kph until I get passed the tunnel and into Katipunan where I can actually go 120.&nbsp; Chipeco says I drive like a maniac, I tell him to shut up.&nbsp; Traffic lights and speed limits are mere suggestions if there are no policemen.&nbsp; The lack of road courtesy is pardoned when class starts in 15 minutes.&nbsp; Of course that&rsquo;s just me being backed up by my pretty fast 1.6 liter engine car.&nbsp; I know you would probably say that I should wake up earlier so I have more travel time and therefore afford to drive slowly.&nbsp; But it&rsquo;s something I&rsquo;ve learned to do.&nbsp; And I don&rsquo;t think it&rsquo;s possible to &ldquo;unlearn&rdquo; something already learned.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s operant conditioning and the law of effect at its finest, where organisms learn the association between a behavior and a consequence.&nbsp; I know I can get to school in 15 minutes (reward), therefore I continue waking up late and taking it easy (behavior).&nbsp; And besides, I think my hippocampus, being the part of the brain that decides what to keep in the form of memory, deemed the way I drive now as the procedural memory of driving I will always retrieve.&nbsp; In short, this is the way I drive and I don&rsquo;t think I can ever change it unless extinction occurs maybe if I get into a big accident.&nbsp; Then I would have a post-traumatic stress disorder.&nbsp; But sans any near-death experience, I can&rsquo;t reboot my hippocampus. Haha. 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Time to talk about something serious.&nbsp; At some point in time a car will get bumped and consequently will suffer a dent.&nbsp; Dents are ugly to look at, a beautiful car deformed; it&rsquo;s just depressing.&nbsp; Well sometimes I get dented too in a sense.&nbsp; Catalysts for this include an emotional ordeal, something shallow like a low score on a big test, or something deep like thinking of the future.&nbsp; Sometimes at night I just become sad and can&rsquo;t exactly pin point why.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s weird, it&rsquo;s hard to explain.&nbsp; But sometimes melancholy somehow manages to creep deep inside my consciousness, completely paralyzing all other thoughts.&nbsp; It takes full control of my mind, and gives birth to thoughts and emotions that are its kin like paranoia, insecurity, hopelessness.&nbsp; Rhetorical questions flood in and I am caught in awe at all the ideas that arise, and the fact that no matter how hard I try, I can never answer them.&nbsp; I can only formulate hunches, mere guesses, but ultimately, I will never know for sure.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s why I hate thinking long term.&nbsp; It scares the hell out of me.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s why I live for the present, having fun, finding my way as I go.&nbsp; But then fun is only fun while it lasts.&nbsp; Afterwards, the stupidity of it all sinks in and creates a splash of melancholia.&nbsp; Wooosh.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To illustrate further: the last 2 months of my recently concluded relationship was not good at all.&nbsp; And sometimes at night I found myself thinking, &ldquo;We rarely agree, we&rsquo;ve grown apart, is this healthy, is this relationship still going anywhere, I wonder how long it will last...&rdquo; And then I&rsquo;m like, &ldquo;Oh shit I&rsquo;m thinking long-term again, help, help, I&rsquo;m scared.&rdquo;&nbsp; So I stopped thinking.&nbsp; I convinced myself that maybe it will be better tomorrow.&nbsp; The shit is but a phase and it soon shall pass.&nbsp; And by doing that, I fixed the dent.&nbsp; The next day I was a brand new car again.&nbsp; Or so I thought.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But it didn&rsquo;t pass.&nbsp; Guess I should have faced the fear.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But what do I fear?&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t fear thinking long-term per se.&nbsp; Now I&rsquo;m realizing that maybe, well psychologically speaking, I have the fear-of-fear thing, a mild one mind you.&nbsp; The only reason why I don&rsquo;t like thinking long-term is because I&rsquo;m scared of the scary things I might think of while thinking about it.&nbsp; Weird, huh?&nbsp; It&rsquo;s like driving.&nbsp; Sometimes I don&rsquo;t even notice that I&rsquo;m over a hundred already.&nbsp; But I&rsquo;m not scared, I don&rsquo;t have a weak heart, it&rsquo;s not like I&rsquo;m going to suffer a stroke on the road.&nbsp; So you see, I don&rsquo;t fear speed per se.&nbsp; What I do fear are stupid pedestrians crossing C5 or maybe the big-ass trucks with poor brakes, and the accidents or deaths that will be caused by them and that will be aggravated by my driving speed.&nbsp; But I still drive fast anyway; I can&rsquo;t help it.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So if you&rsquo;ll ask me to define life, I&rsquo;d say it&rsquo;s a lot like driving.&nbsp; And we all are cars or SUVs or trucks or whatever form of vehicle making our way through this big, big highway called life.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m an Optra &ndash; an ordinary white car with a not so dark tint, rain visors, and a missing emblem.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m not an extravagant car, the color&rsquo;s plain too, but I never vied for luxury or fame anyway.&nbsp; Most of the time I&rsquo;m on the fast lane, shifting gears as circumstance necessitates.&nbsp; Sometimes I make the wrong decision and shift to the wrong gear, or sometimes I do something untimely making me shift too soon or too late.&nbsp; But it&rsquo;s okay to make mistakes as long as you learn from them, right?&nbsp; There are times when some asshole bumps me and I get a dent so I have to go to the shoulder for a while to fix myself up.&nbsp; Sometimes I can do the fixing myself, but there are times that I need friends or a teacher or a parent to stop over and help me heal.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s great when those stop-overs happen because sometimes they don&rsquo;t just fix the dent, they give me an oil change or a car wash as well, and that makes me feel really better and I appreciate the people around me more.&nbsp; And then when I&rsquo;m like brand new again, I go back on the road, driving like I was before.&nbsp; Oftentimes, I don&rsquo;t know where I&rsquo;m going, but that&rsquo;s okay.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s more fun to figure things out when you get there anyway.&nbsp; 

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But that&rsquo;s just me.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Maybe someday I&rsquo;ll get a new car.&nbsp; Maybe I&rsquo;ll have an SUV for a change or a pick-up.&nbsp; Hmmm&hellip;
